{"id":"1911.12817","submitter":"Ruth Gregory","authors":"Michael Appels, Leopoldo Cuspinera, Ruth Gregory, Pavel Krtous, David\n  Kubiznak","title":"Are Superentropic black holes superentropic?","comments":"24 pages, 2 figures, version accepted by JHEP","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/JHEP02(2020)195","report-no":"DCPT-19/33","categories":"hep-th gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study a critical limit in which asymptotically-AdS black holes develop\nmaximal conical deficits and their horizons become non-compact. When applied to\nstationary rotating black holes this limit coincides with the \"ultraspinning\nlimit\" and yields the Superentropic black holes whose entropy was derived\nrecently and found to exceed the maximal possible bound imposed by the Reverse\nIsoperimetric Inequality. To gain more insight into this peculiar result, we\nstudy this limit in the context of accelerated AdS black holes that have\nunequal deficits along the polar axes, hence the maximal deficit need not\nappear on both poles simultaneously. Surprisingly, we find that in the presence\nof acceleration, the critical limit becomes smooth, and is obtained simply by\ntaking various upper bounds in the parameter space that we elucidate. The\nCritical black holes thus obtained have many common features with Superentropic\nblack holes, but are manifestly not superentropic. This raises a concern as to\nwhether Superentropic black holes actually are superentropic. We argue that\nthis may not be so and that the original conclusion is likely attributed to the\ndegeneracy of the resulting first law.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 28 Nov 2019 18:14:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 4 Feb 2020 20:47:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-03-18"}
